      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic can decompose a joint candidate set into per-candidate correctness probabilities and apply selective veto to individual low-confidence candidates rather than the whole set, shifting the majority composition.\",\"mechanism\": \"The repository's data show that a set-level critic decision with fixed precision 0.125 and recall 1.0 yields zero net benefit because it either vetoes all or none. The causal failure is the inability to target the specific wrong candidates within a majority. If instead the critic outputs a calibrated probability for each candidate and the harness subtracts only candidates below threshold tau, the majority can flip from wrong to right. The strict advantage regime is a curve: for any base error in (0.5-p, 0.5+p) where p scales with 1/sqrt(k), there exists a threshold tau making the expected net-fixed-minus-broke positive if and only if the critic's per-candidate score distribution for wrong answers stochastically dominates its distribution for right answers.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"per-candidate critic confidence, not set-level veto\", \"selective candidate subtraction policy with tunable tau\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"any k >= 5\"], \"excludes\": [\"set-level critic with fixed global precision/recall\", \"critic score distributions for right and wrong candidates are identical\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Critic per-candidate score distributions for right and wrong candidates are indistinguishable (KS test p > 0.05) yet thresholded harness strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Critic per-candidate score distributions are separable (KS p < 0.05) but no threshold tau yields positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The selective-veto harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency but a set-level veto harness also exceeds self-consistency by the same margin, contradicting that per-candidate adaptivity is necessary\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: reuse the repository's 44 questions plus 60 new questions spanning base error 0.30-0.70; generate k=5 candidates; instead of set-level critic veto, prompt the critic to output a per-candidate confidence score 0-1; sweep tau in {0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 0.95}; compute per-tau harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke; also run the set-level veto harness for comparison. Confirm: (1) at high tau, FPR on right candidates drops below 0.1 while recall on wrong candidates stays above 0.3; (2) there exists tau where harness strictly beats SC; (3) set-level veto does not match this. Token budget: 104 q * 5 cand * 800 tokens + 104 q * 5 * 600 critic + 104 q * 5 thresholds * 50 eval + analysis ~= 150k.\"}",
