      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses candidate-answer semantic clustering to identify and veto outlier minority clusters that indicate a systematic generation error, rather than evaluating the whole set.\",\"mechanism\": \"The repository's data show that a whole-set critic veto with fixed precision 0.125 and recall 1.0 yields zero net benefit because it cannot distinguish a structurally coherent wrong set from a noisy right set. The causal failure is the lack of structural analysis of the candidate space. If instead the critic clusters candidate answers by semantic similarity and flags the set only if a distinct minority cluster with high internal similarity exists (indicating a systematic error mode), it selectively catches systematic generation failures. The strict advantage regime is a curve: for any base error in (0.5-p, 0.5+p) where p scales with 1/sqrt(k), there exists a clustering similarity threshold tau making the expected net-fixed-minus-broke positive if and only if systematic errors (producing tight minority clusters) occur at a higher rate than random errors.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"semantic clustering-based critic veto, not whole-set fixed decision\", \"clustering similarity threshold policy with tunable tau\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"any k >= 5\"], \"excludes\": [\"whole-set critic veto with fixed global precision/recall\", \"systematic errors occur at a rate <= random errors\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Systematic errors occur at a rate <= random errors yet clustering-based harness strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Systematic errors occur at a rate > random errors but no clustering threshold tau yields positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The clustering-based harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency but a whole-set veto harness also exceeds self-consistency by the same margin, contradicting that structural analysis is necessary\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: reuse the repository's 44 questions plus 60 new questions spanning base error 0.30-0.70; generate k=5 candidates; embed candidate answers and cluster by cosine similarity; instead of whole-set critic veto, flag sets with a tight minority cluster (similarity > tau); sweep tau in {0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 0.95, 0.99}; compute per-tau harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke; also run the whole-set veto harness for comparison. Confirm: (1) at high tau, false flags on right-majority sets drop below 0.1 while catching systematic wrong-majority sets stays above 0.3; (2) there exists tau where harness strictly beats SC; (3) whole-set veto does not match this. Token budget: 104 q * 5 cand * 800 tokens + 104 q * 5 * 200 embedding + 104 q * 5 thresholds * 50 eval + analysis ~= 55k.\"}",
